free_txt: From compilers: for Fig. 4,6,7 (sub 9,11,12) different
arbitrary scales are given.
The Aldermaston multigap spectrograph was used.
The targets used were self-supporting, nominally
100 mu-g/cm2 thick and prepared by electrolytic
deposition onto a backing of natural copper which was
dissolved off in trichloracetic acid.
Isotopic analysis of the sample used for target
preparation.
Target                Isotopic abundance (%)
54Fe       56Fe       57Fe       58Fe
The error are of scanning of the emulsions
(5%) or statistical, whichever is the greater.

Systematic error

Different normalisation methods were used:
using cross section for 56Fe(d,p)57Fe reaction
normalisation of 58Fe(d,d)58Fe to optical model
predictions
normalisation of 58Fe(d,d)58Fe to data for
56Fe(d,d)56Fe for angle less 80 degr.
mean
The absolute cross sections were obtained in two ways.
a) The relative yields of the elastic scattering and of
the (d,p) reactions were measured simultaneously and
the data for the (d,d) reaction normalized to the cross
sections predicted by an optical model fit to the data.
b) Relative differential cross sections of the
56Fe(d,d) reaction for theta 35 - 175 degr., and the
58Fe(d,d) reaction for theta <35 degr., were obtained
using the Aldermaston multigap spectrograph. These were
placed on an absolute scale by normalization to
absolute values of the (d,d) cross sections for theta
<=65 degr. The cross sections for the 58Fe(d,p)59Fe
reaction were then obtained from the relative yields
of the (d,p) reaction with the 56Fe and 58Fe
constituents in the target used to study the
58Fe(d,p)59Fe reaction.

Absolute cross sections for the levels strongly excited
in the (t,p) reaction were obtained by normalizing
the yield of the (t,t) reaction to the values predicted
by an optical model fit to the elastic scattering data.
To obtain absolute cross sections for all levels the
data obtained in the manner described above were
normalized to those obtained in the separate exposure
for the (t,p) reaction.
